\begin_layout Problem
Show that the Brewster's angle does not exist for S-polarized light for
 any 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Sketch the ratios of reflected and transmitted fields with incident field
 as a function of the incident angle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
S-polarized light means the 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 field is perpendicular to the plane of incidence (the 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset

-plane) so it is pointing in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 direction.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 field lies in the 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset

-plane.
 We want the Fresnel equations for S-polarized light.
 The boundary conditions are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(\text{i})\qquad(E_{0I}+E_{0R})_{y} & = & (E_{0T})_{y}\\
(\text{ii})\qquad(B_{0I}+B_{0R})_{z} & = & (B_{0T})_{z}\\
(\text{iii})\qquad\frac{1}{\mu_{1}}(B_{0I}+B_{0R})_{x} & = & \frac{1}{\mu_{2}}(B_{0T})_{x}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From (ii), since 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}=E_{0}/v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
B_{0I}\sin\theta_{I}+B_{0R}\sin\theta_{R} & = & B_{0T}\sin\theta_{T}\\
\sin\theta_{I}(B_{0I}+B_{0R}) & = & B_{0T}\sin\theta_{T}\qquad(\theta_{R}=\theta_{I})\\
B_{0I}+B_{0R} & = & B_{0T}\frac{\sin\theta_{T}}{\sin\theta_{I}}\\
\frac{E_{0I}}{v_{1}}+\frac{E_{0R}}{v_{1}} & = & \frac{E_{0T}}{v_{2}}\frac{v_{2}}{v_{1}}\qquad(\text{Snell's Law})\\
E_{0I}+E_{0R} & = & E_{0T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From (iii)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{\mu_{1}}(-\frac{E_{0I}}{v_{1}}\cos\theta_{I}+\frac{E_{0R}}{v_{1}}\cos\theta_{R}) & = & -\frac{1}{\mu_{2}v_{2}}E_{0T}\cos\theta_{T}\\
-\frac{\cos\theta_{I}}{\mu_{1}v_{1}}(E_{0I}-E_{0R}) & = & -\frac{\cos\theta_{T}}{\mu_{2}v_{2}}E_{0T}\\
E_{0I}-E_{0R} & = & \frac{\mu_{1}v_{1}}{\mu_{2}v_{2}}\frac{\cos\theta_{T}}{\cos\theta_{I}}E_{0T}\\
 & = & \frac{\mu_{1}n_{2}}{\mu_{2}n_{1}}\frac{\cos\theta_{T}}{\cos\theta_{I}}E_{0T}\\
 & = & \beta\alpha E_{0T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So now, substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0R}=E_{0T}-E_{0I}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{0I}-E_{0T}+E_{0I} & = & \alpha\beta E_{0T}\\
E_{0T} & = & \frac{2}{1+\alpha\beta}E_{0I}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This means 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{0R} & = & (\frac{2}{1+\alpha\beta}-1)E_{0I}\\
 & = & \frac{1-\alpha\beta}{1+\alpha\beta}E_{0I}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

These are the Fresnel equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{0T}=\frac{2}{1+\alpha\beta}E_{0I}\qquad E_{0R}=\frac{1-\alpha\beta}{1+\alpha\beta}E_{0I}
\]

\end_inset

Brewster's angle is the angle of incidence where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0R}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So we want 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\alpha\beta=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1 & = & \alpha\beta\\
 & = & \beta\frac{\cos\theta_{T}}{\cos\theta_{I}}\\
 & = & \beta\frac{\sqrt{1-\sin^{2}\theta_{T}}}{\cos\theta_{I}}\\
 & = & \beta\frac{\sqrt{1-(\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}})^{2}\sin^{2}\theta_{I}}}{\cos\theta_{I}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}\approx\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}\approx\frac{1}{\beta}$
\end_inset

, so this condition becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1 & = & \frac{\sqrt{\beta^{2}-\sin^{2}\theta_{I}}}{\cos\theta_{I}}\\
\beta^{2} & = & \cos^{2}\theta_{I}+\sin^{2}\theta_{I}=1\\
\beta & = & 1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

But this will only happen if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=n_{2}$
\end_inset

..
 which means there is no interface.
 So there is no Brewster's angle for S-polarized light reflecting off an
 interface.
\end_layout

